WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
My name is Marc van de Meulebroeke. I work at Novartis, and I just want to say a few

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:19.280
motivating words on why we're doing what we're doing and what you can expect to hear today.

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:24.240
We start from the insight that graphics and visuals are such an important component of

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:30.240
the work we do as quantitative scientists. They're so important for ourselves to gain

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:37.959
insights into data, as well as for communicating results and conclusions to our stakeholders.

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:42.720
And if you've been following all those coronavirus charts out there for the past few weeks, like

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:48.799
I did, you will agree that graphics are key to understanding what's going on.

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:56.560
Unfortunately, however, we are not always good at creating effective graphs.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:01.799
How often do we see or even create ineffective visualizations?

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:11.519
And do we even know which choices or features make a graph effective for a particular purpose or audience?

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:16.400
This is our first focus, to convey this understanding.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:26.639
And this point is actually part of a wider initiative beyond today's webinar, and you will find a corresponding link at the end of these slides.

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:33.839
Secondly, once we do know what makes an effective graph, how easily can we actually implement it?

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:37.680
That is, create it quickly and with minimal effort.

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:46.120
This is our second focus, the development of an R package that has good graphical principles sort of built in,

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:54.320
building upon many of the great packages out there and minimizing the code required for the user.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:02:03.760
We quickly realized that these themes are of common interest across Roche, Novartis and probably many other companies and institutions.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:08.360
So we've started to team up and tackle them together.

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:15.679
And one of the goals today is also to call for additional interested contributors.

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:21.160
Which leads me to today's agenda.

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:32.039
After this introduction, my colleague Mark Bailey from Novartis will speak about the principles of effective visual communication generally.

00:02:32.039 --> 00:02:45.320
He will then hand over to Charlotte Fruchtenicht and Diego Saldana from Roche, who will focus more specifically and a bit more technically on the R package which we've started to develop.

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:52.199
The goal of this package, as I said earlier, is to make it really easy to implement those good principles in practice,

00:02:52.199 --> 00:02:58.759
specifically in a health care or drug development context, which is where we work.

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:10.440
All this is work in progress. And at the end of the webinar, we will call for further contributors and we will hopefully also have a few minutes for Q&A.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:14.880
So with that, Mark, do you want to start?

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:26.039
Thank you, Mark. So effective data visualisation is a key skill for all quantitative scientists, including statisticians, epidemiologists or data scientists,

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:34.880
whatever your current title is. Traditionally, this is a skill has not been a primary focus in the training and development of quantitative scientists.

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:39.839
In graduate degrees, the focus is often on analytical and technical competencies.

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:46.600
This skill of visual communication is often self-taught or developed later on in the job.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:55.559
So effective visualisation is extremely important. It is a key skill that allows us to convey complex concepts and information to others.

00:03:55.559 --> 00:03:59.800
If we get this right, it helps support appropriate decisions or actions.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:07.279
If we get this wrong, it can lead to misinformation, confusion or even harm, especially in clinical and medical research.

00:04:07.279 --> 00:04:13.639
The visualisation on the right is a good recent example of this covering the current coronavirus pandemic.

00:04:13.639 --> 00:04:21.279
The visualisation was recently published in The New York Times. It displays the concept of social distancing and why it is important.

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:28.440
It is important because it helps break the transmission chain. The graphic also illustrates the concept of exponential growth.

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:34.720
This is something we've heard a lot of recently. Here we see an infected individual who goes on to infect two others.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:42.440
They in turn infect two others until we begin to see many individuals infected with the virus, all stemming from a single person.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:48.279
By practising social distancing, we may break this chain, therefore reducing the number of subsequent infections,

00:04:48.279 --> 00:04:53.320
which could be substantial, as displayed in the bottom graphic.

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:58.480
We are not always good at it. On the right is an example from a clinical study report.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:03.640
Waterfall plots are commonly used to report treatment response in oncology clinical trials.

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:08.959
Aesthetically, this plot doesn't look good, from the choice of patterns to the general look and feel.

00:05:08.959 --> 00:05:13.000
For me, it feels like it was produced by a typewriter rather than modern software.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.040
There's a lot not to like about this plot.

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:20.320
But as I said earlier, if we get visual communication wrong, it can lead to the wrong conclusions.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:25.040
And in working in medical and clinical research, this can often result in harm.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:30.320
So apart from the aesthetic limitations, the real failing of this graph is not the look and feel,

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:36.959
but that the graph expects the reader to make calculations mentally to compare treatment effects across multiple doses.

00:05:36.959 --> 00:05:43.720
Waterfall plots are often used to support decision making, especially in critical indications found in oncology.

00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:51.519
So asking the reader to make those calculations mentally isn't an effective way to communicate.

00:05:51.519 --> 00:05:57.600
So what do we mean by effective? We don't necessarily mean beautiful.

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:02.720
So we don't really mean to focus on the beautiful.

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:08.440
So to illustrate here is an example of a visually appealing graph from David McAnalyst.

00:06:08.440 --> 00:06:11.519
He is a data artist and journalist from the UK.

00:06:11.519 --> 00:06:17.880
The visualisation is called Mountains out of molehills, a timeline of global media scare stories.

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:23.959
The visualisation attempts to investigate the number of news story reports and if there is a sense of overreporting.

00:06:23.959 --> 00:06:27.200
And so this could cause unnecessary panic.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:34.480
It covers earlier pandemics such as SARS, bird flu and spine flu, but also video games and killer wasps.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:42.119
Visually, it is appealing and draws you in, but I would argue it's not effective as key information is hidden away in the legend.

00:06:42.119 --> 00:06:47.720
So if you look at the legend, there are numbers and brackets that provide the deaths associated with each story.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:50.839
It's very difficult to see, I can imagine.

00:06:50.839 --> 00:06:54.839
This information is important to determine if there really is overreporting,

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:58.279
but the information is not factored into the main body of the graph.

00:06:58.279 --> 00:07:02.399
Also, the subtitle uses languages such as scare stories.

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:09.959
It has comparisons to annual seasonal flu deaths and it also has comparisons to topics such as video gaming.

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:16.959
All of these design choices indirectly influence the reader, which can then influence decision making.

00:07:16.959 --> 00:07:19.679
So beautiful and effective, that's what we really want.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:24.959
So here's an example of a recent effective visualization published by The Economist.

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:29.839
The visualization captures a recent phrase that we hear a lot of now, flatten the curve.

00:07:29.839 --> 00:07:32.799
The graph summarizes this concept really well.

00:07:32.799 --> 00:07:37.959
So we have two distributions of a time which represent the number of infections in the population.

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:47.920
Each distribution represents a strategy. Strategy one for not taking preventative measures such as social distancing and strategy two that does.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.799
You can see that strategy two reduces the peak of the distribution through social distancing.

00:07:52.799 --> 00:07:59.440
This strategy extends the epidemic over a longer period of time, but reduces the peak number of infections.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:05.559
This special visualization is effective in introducing this concept of flattening the curve.

00:08:05.559 --> 00:08:10.440
But can we be even more effective? So here's another version of the same graph.

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.640
Aesthetically, it's not as appealing as the previous one.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:21.799
But by adding a dotted line and a simple annotation health care system capacity, this visualization now highlights the why.

00:08:21.799 --> 00:08:28.239
Why do we want to flatten the infection curve and spread an epidemic over a longer period of time?

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:32.599
The purpose of flattening the curve is not to overwhelm the health care system.

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:38.799
So the dotted line illustrates that the first strategy would result in more infections than the health care system could cope with.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:43.799
This, sadly, can have terrible consequences that we are currently witnessing now.

00:08:43.799 --> 00:08:50.919
So both graphs are very effective ways to convey complex concepts to the population and get messages out there.

00:08:50.919 --> 00:08:55.640
And I just want to highlight that both of these slides were influenced by a tweet from Carl Bergstrom.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:03.679
The link is there if you want to follow up on it. So effective visualization is effective visual communication.

00:09:03.679 --> 00:09:07.880
Effective graphs are visually appealing, intuitive, legible.

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:14.359
Then use the correct graph type and axis scales. Then use proximity and alignment to facilitate comparisons.

00:09:14.359 --> 00:09:19.280
Then use labels and annotations to add clarity to the message, as I illustrated before.

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:24.159
And more importantly, effective use of visualizations enable clear and impactful communication.

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:29.840
Evaluate our influence with our stakeholders and facilitate informed decision making.

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:38.039
This is one of the main motivations behind the collaboration that we are presenting today and the initial design of the Bizarre Package.

00:09:38.039 --> 00:09:40.440
But how do we become more effective?

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:44.840
Myself and colleagues at Novartis have been thinking about this topic for a number of years.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:50.119
We've tried a number of approaches to try and address this question, from reading all the literature available,

00:09:50.119 --> 00:09:58.320
defining best practices, developing galleries of code, newsletters to highlight the importance of the topic, to handing out cheat sheets.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:04.200
And we've had various levels of success. But to make this concept stick and to be easier to remember,

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:08.880
we recently defined what we call the three laws for effective visual communication.

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:13.679
Have a clear purpose, show the data clearly and make the message obvious.

00:10:13.679 --> 00:10:18.479
You can think of these three laws as superheroes. So have a clear purpose.

00:10:18.479 --> 00:10:24.280
This is really about why do we need this graph? So we should really know the purpose of creating the graph.

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:27.840
And this is really related also to data analysis itself.

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:36.799
We should identify the quantitative evidence to support the purpose and also identify the audience and focus the design to support their needs.

00:10:36.799 --> 00:10:46.119
Show the data clearly. This is about avoiding misrepresentation, choosing the appropriate graph type to display the data, maximizing data to ink ratio.

00:10:46.119 --> 00:10:49.760
So this is really just a complex way of saying keep it simple.

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:57.640
Finally, make the message obvious. So using proximity and alignment to aid in comparisons, minimize mental arithmetic.

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:07.119
This is really going back to the waterfall plot where you really don't want the reader to be doing summations in their head and using colors and annotations to highlight important details.

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:17.159
So I'll now go through each of these three laws in more detail. So law one, have a clear purpose.

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:24.239
This first law is really advanced common sense. It follows typical planning questions such as why, what, who and where.

00:11:24.239 --> 00:11:30.599
So why do I need a graph and what is its purpose? Is it to explore data or to deliver a message?

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:38.520
What evidence is available to support this purpose? This could be data sets, new experiments, simulations, for example.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:44.440
Whatever. OK. Who is my intended audience? Is it a mix of specialists or non-specialists or both?

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:52.200
You really need to think about who this audience is and support their needs. And the where, where will I publish and what are the constraints there?

00:11:52.200 --> 00:12:02.080
So for the where, we may identify certain formats such as a Word document, a PowerPoint, PowerPoint presentation or a Markdown notebook or a Shiny app.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:10.239
And really the design and the purpose and the principles that we have really, really is important for all of these different formats.

00:12:10.239 --> 00:12:19.000
But depending on the format, some of these principles may apply and the design choices may vary.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.239
Another aspect to this law is to identify what are the underlying questions you're trying to address.

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:33.520
So here I've highlighted an article by Roger Penn that discusses his thoughts on John Tukey, exploratory data analysis and design thinking.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:37.440
He argues that better analyses are related to the quality of the question.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:41.599
So more time spent on defining better questions is time well spent.

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:50.119
And this is related to the famous Tukey quote, an approximate answer to the right question is worth a great deal more than the precise answer to the wrong question.

00:12:50.119 --> 00:12:59.039
So the message here is to spend more time thinking about your question prior to an analysis or designing a visualisation.

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:03.000
Another aspect to this law is why are you creating visualisation?

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:09.239
So thinking about this aspect can help identify the audience and their needs, which in turn helps with the design.

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:17.520
So, for example, if you want to dig into data, get familiar with the data or find the story in my data, then the audience is normally you.

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:23.159
If you want to communicate the results or to tell the story behind the data, then the audience is someone else.

00:13:23.159 --> 00:13:26.479
So being clear on the purpose is important here.

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:34.440
For example, if you're designing a visualisation to be presented to a group of stakeholders where you have three minutes to get your recommendations across,

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:41.280
do you really want the audience to play? Where's Wally? Or in the case of America, where's Waldo?

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:47.640
And if you're really interested, Wally is in the middle of the picture here.

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:52.320
Law two, show the data clearly.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:14:00.880
The key part of this law is not to lie or represent with data. Try to be open and transparent with your analysis and the reporting of it.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:05.159
Here we have an example from YouGov, an important topic of pizza toppings.

00:14:05.159 --> 00:14:13.960
The visualisation displays a pizza pie chart. The visualisation is confusing as the numbers add up to way beyond 100%.

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:18.359
Another thing that's confusing is mushroom is the UK's most liked pizza topping.

00:14:18.359 --> 00:14:26.400
So as a Scotsman, I really find this hard to believe. Another aspect of this law is to be transparent.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:31.039
Here I've displayed a response from YouGov to clarify the purpose of their chart.

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:35.760
The intent was not to display a pie chart, but to present percentages from a survey.

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:41.159
Here we see that being clear and transparent builds trust and it helps with communication.

00:14:41.159 --> 00:14:50.080
Another aspect to this apology is that it highlights the need to think carefully about your design and the graph type.

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:53.200
So choosing the correct graph type aids in interpretation.

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:58.479
So thinking about the purpose of the graph can help identify appropriate graph types.

00:14:58.479 --> 00:15:01.239
Often we don't need to reinvent the wheel here.

00:15:01.239 --> 00:15:10.239
For example, if we want to show a deviation, a correlation or a ranking, then there are common graph types that we can select from.

00:15:10.239 --> 00:15:18.559
Another aspect to think about in terms of graph type is what information do you want to convey?

00:15:18.559 --> 00:15:23.159
So here is an example of the same data displayed six different ways.

00:15:23.159 --> 00:15:30.039
The pie and donut charts in panels A and B make it difficult to see the order of magnitude of some of the segments.

00:15:30.039 --> 00:15:35.520
I need to compare areas or angles. These attributes are not easy to compare.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:42.000
The donut chart even omits the angles and bends the areas to make it more challenging to make these comparisons.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.280
The mosaic plot in panel C only relies on areas.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:48.440
Again, it's hard to compare across categories.

00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:54.400
It is better to use lengths with a common baseline or positions on a common scale, such as a bar chart or dot plot.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:16:03.599
The bar chart in panel D, though, introduces a fake dimension, which is unnecessary and makes it hard to compare numerical values from the height of the bars.

00:16:03.599 --> 00:16:07.280
Panels E and F are simple and show the data clearly.

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:10.799
They also order the data by magnitude to aid comparison even further.

00:16:10.799 --> 00:16:17.359
So you're really not making the reader work or do the mental arithmetic in their head.

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:22.119
The dot plot in panel F uses minimal ink and draws the eye to the position of the dots.

00:16:22.119 --> 00:16:27.559
So it's probably the most effective way of displaying the data.

00:16:27.559 --> 00:16:29.559
Choose the right scale for your data.

00:16:29.559 --> 00:16:33.880
So try to avoid plotting log-normally distributed variables on a linear scale.

00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:40.039
This can lead to misleading interpretation, especially when you introduce lines to encode uncertainty.

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:47.640
So in this example, the uncertainty appears to increase above 1, which is unity, but this is an artifact of the choice of the scale.

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:52.200
Using a log scale resolves this issue.

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:57.799
Another important aspect related to this is time and how that is displayed.

00:16:57.799 --> 00:17:03.239
So space measurements proportional to the time they were measured.

00:17:03.239 --> 00:17:04.239
So what do we mean by that?

00:17:04.239 --> 00:17:08.439
So measurements that are displayed close together are perceived to be closer in time.

00:17:08.439 --> 00:17:12.439
Not reflecting this in your visualization could introduce a visual bias.

00:17:12.439 --> 00:17:20.560
So, for example, slopes or trajectories may appear steeper or less so than they typically are.

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:24.280
Law 3, make the message obvious.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:32.719
A key aspect of this law is not to assume that the reader will understand what messages or information you're trying to convey.

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:40.520
You have to really work at it to get them to understand this information or what you're trying to convey to them.

00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:44.400
A simple illustration of this is to try and not to set text at an angle.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:47.319
Think of alternatives such as transposing the graph.

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:52.199
So the left-hand plot, we are essentially asking the reader to tilt their head to read the text.

00:17:52.199 --> 00:17:55.359
Do we really want to give readers neck strain?

00:17:55.359 --> 00:18:02.439
A simple transposing of the graph allows us to resolve this issue and also introduces a more effective visualization.

00:18:02.439 --> 00:18:05.599
Also, try to avoid unnecessary color.

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:11.839
Avoid using color to differentiate between categories of the same variable.

00:18:11.839 --> 00:18:17.560
This can introduce confusion in a similar way to the previous pizza example from YouGov.

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:25.880
Also, introducing unnecessary color when it's not required limits us to when we really do need to use color later on.

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:28.920
For example, use color when it adds value.

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:33.520
Use a bold, saturated or contrasting color to emphasize important details.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.839
So the left-hand plot, our eyes are naturally drawn to the top of the bar.

00:18:37.839 --> 00:18:41.239
The right-hand plot, we introduce a contrasting color.

00:18:41.239 --> 00:18:43.959
Now our eyes are drawn to the bottom of the bars.

00:18:43.959 --> 00:18:52.199
This is an important design choice that allows us to highlight key information and can be used to really highlight important messaging.

00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:56.640
And here's an example of using annotations and labels to help with messages.

00:18:56.640 --> 00:19:01.040
So use labels and annotations to tell stories about the data and models.

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:05.079
On the left-hand side, we have a typical dose response plot.

00:19:05.079 --> 00:19:09.280
By adding annotations such as active control and target dose on the right-hand side,

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:12.000
we start to provide more contextual information for the reader.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.359
And then we can start to get to the why of the plot.

00:19:14.359 --> 00:19:23.479
So think back to the platinum of the curve plot where we add in the dotted line to indicate the healthcare system capacity.

00:19:23.479 --> 00:19:29.239
So finally, here's an example that we created of a visualization that tries to follow all three principles.

00:19:29.239 --> 00:19:33.040
The analysis is a subgroup comparison of a genetic marker.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:35.880
The analysis is a repeated measures model over time.

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:40.119
We use the title to indicate a conclusion or recommendation from the analysis.

00:19:40.119 --> 00:19:44.400
So genetic marker positive is not predicted for treatment response.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:48.640
We use annotations to indicate the direction of the treatment benefit.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:57.599
And we also highlight the main time point, which is our primary analysis at week 12 with a dotted circle.

00:19:57.599 --> 00:20:00.839
Instead of legends, we use annotations to indicate each subgroup.

00:20:00.839 --> 00:20:05.479
And we also use color to differentiate between subgroups.

00:20:05.479 --> 00:20:10.520
So if you're interested to learn more about the three laws and some of the principles I've introduced today,

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:15.239
I'd recommend that you visit the website below graphicsprinciples.github.io.

00:20:15.239 --> 00:20:21.640
We have a cheat sheet there that summarizes a lot of these principles and it's developed using R.

00:20:21.640 --> 00:20:24.280
There are also other great resources out there that you can use.

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:30.760
For example, the book by Jean-Luc Dumont really introduces scientific communication.

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:33.839
It's really an exemplar book that everyone should read.

00:20:33.839 --> 00:20:38.000
If you're really interested in data visualization, I would recommend the other two books,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:42.560
the data visualization from Kieran Healy and also the book by Klaus Wilk,

00:20:42.560 --> 00:20:50.719
which focus on not only just the principles of data visualization, but also how to do this in R.

00:20:50.719 --> 00:20:55.079
So effective data visualization is effective visual communication.

00:20:55.079 --> 00:20:58.839
Effective visualizations enable clear and impactful communication.

00:20:58.839 --> 00:21:04.760
They evaluate our influence with stakeholders and they facilitate informed decision making.

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:11.680
To help design effective visualizations, remember the three laws, purpose, clarity and message.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:18.520
So typically now I would do a handover that would require either a strong or a moderate handshakes,

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:23.479
possibly a prolonged high five, maybe just a normal high five or a prolonged fist bump.

00:21:23.479 --> 00:21:29.719
Given the current situation, I'll just do a virtual fist bump to Shalota.

00:21:29.719 --> 00:21:32.040
Thank you, Mark.

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:40.680
So what you've seen in this first section is how important it is to implement graphics principles for effective visual communication.

00:21:40.680 --> 00:21:47.400
But the reason why we are giving this webinar is that you often don't see that in typical data science analyses.

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:54.800
And the reason for that is that implementing those visual principles can be quite tedious and time consuming

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:58.359
and adding quite a bit of extra overhead on the coding side.

00:21:58.359 --> 00:22:07.319
So especially early on in projects, data scientists tend to skip a lot of those principles to just get on with their project.

00:22:07.319 --> 00:22:12.119
For example, if you look on the right, you can see that creating this relatively simple dose response curve,

00:22:12.119 --> 00:22:16.719
that's not even adhering to all the principles that Mark just described.

00:22:16.719 --> 00:22:27.280
And you see that actually it requires as much extra code to style the diagram and add annotations as it does to plot the actual data.

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:32.199
So because of this extra work, we often skip it.

00:22:32.199 --> 00:22:37.000
But then downstream, for example, when communicating to external stakeholders,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:46.560
we have to keep up with that work and actually implement new versions of the plots and figures and tables that we did early on.

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:56.560
Exploratory projects. So we thought this is something we probably have to change if we want to be more effective in the way we communicate our results.

00:22:56.560 --> 00:23:02.719
And if you go to the next slide, Mark. There is actually an additional point.

00:23:02.719 --> 00:23:11.400
And as Mark mentioned, we there are different stakeholders or different audience to your reporting outcomes.

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:15.599
So early on in a project, this might be just for you and yourself, like yourself.

00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:22.599
And you might remember all the work you've done, all the data manipulations, and you might not need a lot of additional annotation.

00:23:22.599 --> 00:23:27.439
But usually you're working in a team, at least in clinical development.

00:23:27.439 --> 00:23:35.640
And so you have additional stakeholders that might look at the outputs that you create, maybe figures or tables.

00:23:35.640 --> 00:23:44.640
And you might actually have those stakeholders take those outputs and then further use them to communicate their insights in their teams.

00:23:44.680 --> 00:23:56.599
So it's actually quite important that whatever you create in your analysis cannot be taken out of context and that at any time it is possible to reproduce the output that you created,

00:23:56.599 --> 00:24:01.359
tables and figures, and also trace where the data came from.

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:07.839
So on the right, you can see a typical table shell for baseline demographics in a cohort.

00:24:07.839 --> 00:24:16.119
And as you can see clearly, we're showing a table here because Mark showed a lot of figures and we want to make sure that you all are aware that outputs can also be tables.

00:24:16.119 --> 00:24:24.520
So if you have a table, you can see that there is a lot of metadata in addition to the actual demographics that are being annotated.

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:32.520
So, for example, every table and figure should have a title and it should name the data source and the version the data comes from.

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:44.359
So if that plot or that table finds its way into a PowerPoint presentation, it's easy to trace back where it came from and at what time point the analysis was done.

00:24:44.359 --> 00:24:52.000
We should always have also a part as part of the rendered object, the information about the abbreviations and table columns that are being used,

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:00.000
the statistical tests that were employed, as well as some baseline information or basic information about the cohort, such as sample size.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:09.040
Generally, also, we would like to have the reports that we create to be harmonized across the different visualizations, plots and figures again,

00:25:09.040 --> 00:25:16.160
so that, for example, the same treatment refers is always coded by the same color in different plots.

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:29.079
So there is this second layer in addition to visual communication and those graphics principles that Mark just introduced that we often have to take into consideration in our data science project.

00:25:29.079 --> 00:25:43.119
And again, looking at the metadata, you can imagine that annotating all of these information can create quite a bit of overhead on the coding side and is often skipped early on in projects.

00:25:43.119 --> 00:25:50.479
So if you go to the next slide. So we realize this is something we have to change.

00:25:50.479 --> 00:26:04.439
And as Mark said in the beginning, it's it's probably an issue that not only data science teams at Roche and Novartis have, but also a lot of other people doing analytics work across the industry and beyond.

00:26:04.439 --> 00:26:13.599
And so we thought we want to implement something like a toolbox that helps us integrate graphical principles in our data science and analytics projects.

00:26:13.599 --> 00:26:26.239
We didn't want to do that in a vacuum, though, so we reached out to not only other data scientists in our in our own teams, but also important stakeholders like therapeutic area scientists or clinical scientists

00:26:26.239 --> 00:26:36.239
to better understand what they would like to see in typical reports that we create and what the crucial aspects are that should never be missing.

00:26:36.239 --> 00:26:45.760
And with that, we came up with a bunch of development considerations that the toolbox we wanted to develop should always adhere to.

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:57.800
And the first one is really not creating extra work. So it should integrate seamlessly into our analytics and reporting workflows, and it should work well with the tools we are already using.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:03.920
So often this is the analysis are done in R, so it should play well with the tidyverse.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:19.400
Plotting should probably be done using ggplot and then it should be rendered in different output formats like R Markdown using like HTML output as well as Word and LaTeX or interactively using Shiny.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:29.040
And the package or toolbox should be suitable for our special use cases and clinical development, but might also reach beyond.

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:46.520
And it should be flexible enough so that also expert users find the tools useful and like to use them to ease some of the coding burden and create, for example, these additional metadata objects around the visual output they are already creating.

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:52.439
As Mark said, the audience might actually change for your for your outputs as a project evolves.

00:27:52.439 --> 00:28:02.359
And so the toolbox should allow us to easily adapt to these different target audiences without having to repeat the actual analysis.

00:28:02.359 --> 00:28:20.239
That could be, for example, by exploring different visualizations of the same data set and see which one helps us adhere to those three laws that Mark introduced, especially which one helps us to make convey the message clearly and help in decision making.

00:28:20.239 --> 00:28:26.479
And as I said, the the outputs might make their way through different stages of stakeholders as well.

00:28:26.479 --> 00:28:28.520
So it should be possible to export them.

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:44.000
And there was something very, very critical from our teammates on the therapeutic area side so that you can output them, for example, so that they can easily take the output and present it in their own presentations.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.119
And so if you go to the next slide.

00:28:48.119 --> 00:28:56.959
This quickly led us to the idea of developing an R package because R is increasingly popular and widely used in our teams.

00:28:56.959 --> 00:29:04.119
And it already comes with a bunch of really excellent existing packages that solve parts of the problems that we just stated.

00:29:04.119 --> 00:29:12.079
So there are packages already that allow very flexible plotting opportunities, for example, ggplot.

00:29:12.079 --> 00:29:22.400
And we thought actually building on those on those packages and standing on the shoulders of giants here will make the work less hard for us.

00:29:22.400 --> 00:29:29.599
The other nice part about using R is that it is flexible towards multiple analysis questions and stages of the workflow.

00:29:29.599 --> 00:29:38.880
And if we developed a package that had different functions, we could actually build in the flexibility that was so requested by our users.

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:42.000
We obviously can have the documentation and testing.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:55.040
And given that it's open source, it's really easy to collaborate across companies and even industries in the future and contribute content to go to the next slide.

00:29:55.040 --> 00:30:06.000
So that's why we are now presenting the vis R package in its current form, which is actually is still very early experimental phase.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:14.439
Or you could actually call it a prototype, maybe which we which we developed and would like to hear feedback of you all later on as well.

00:30:14.439 --> 00:30:27.920
We thought to there were there are a few architecture considerations we put in in order to implement those considerations and requirements that we got in our earliest stakeholder interviews.

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:34.119
So the first one was really about this integration, seamless integration into the tidy verse in our analysis workflow.

00:30:34.119 --> 00:30:41.839
So we thought whatever we do, it should interact with the plier and the modeling packages and plotting should be built on ggplot.

00:30:41.839 --> 00:30:55.400
We also want to keep full transparency on data modifications, first of all, for the reproducible reporting aspect, but also for being able to scale projects across different stages.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:31:06.479
And that led us to this decoupled design that you can see on the right where we actually take our input data, let's say, for example, one row per sample, one row per patient data set.

00:31:06.479 --> 00:31:18.560
And then we have dedicated functions that take care of the data wrangling and the modeling before another set of functions takes care of the visualization.

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:24.839
And that visualization ideally adheres to the graphical principles that Mark just described before.

00:31:24.839 --> 00:31:35.000
And then last but not least, we have a separate set of functions, again, that takes care of the separate that takes care of the styling of the outputs.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.760
So there shouldn't be any hard coded theming, for example, in the plotting function.

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:45.400
But that is then taken care of and allows us, for example, to adapt the visualization to corporate designs.

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:59.000
But it also allows us to adapt the visualization to be consistent across the report where, for example, the treatments are always colored in the same way across.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:12.839
We mentioned before as well that in addition to being flexible, though, the coding of and adhering to those graphical principles shouldn't add a lot of overhead to the coding work you're doing as a data scientist anyways.

00:32:12.839 --> 00:32:24.839
So we thought it would be great to have, in addition to those individual decoupled functions, the wrapper functions that allow you to explore different visualizations for typical analysis questions.

00:32:24.839 --> 00:32:37.920
So one typical question in clinical development when working with a patient cohort in the beginning is, for example, to see how many of those patients in the data set adhere to a set of inclusion and exclusion criteria.

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:41.880
And you might want to show the cohort attrition.

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:45.400
And there are different ways of doing that. And Diego will talk about it a bit later.

00:32:45.400 --> 00:33:01.000
But having a wrapper function that allows you to explore these different visualizations can then help you quickly find out which visualization might be the best one to convey your message clearly to the target audience you're currently designing your report for.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:13.400
If you go to the next slide. So this was all very theoretical so far, and it's going to stay a bit theoretical for the next two slides before I hand over to Diego.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:25.319
But what I want to show here is really how this would look if you implemented it for a typical question, another typical question around time to event analysis.

00:33:25.319 --> 00:33:40.680
And so by having decoupled functions, if we had our initial input data model for patient data that has, for example, intervention like treatment and then the time of follow up or time to event and the status at the end,

00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:48.640
then we wouldn't go directly from this input data model to the plot, but we would go through three individual steps.

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:57.880
The first one is really taking this input data and have an estimator function that computes the estimate, in this case, the survival model.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:10.040
And after cleaning that with Broom, we get a data table or a table as an interim data model, which we can then build our visualizations on.

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:18.439
And in this case, for example, would contain the time, the stratum, as well as the estimates at different time points and the confidence intervals.

00:34:18.439 --> 00:34:24.360
And these can then be easily passed on to ggplot, for example, for visualization.

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:28.600
As I said before, we didn't want to reinvent the wheel where this was necessary.

00:34:28.600 --> 00:34:39.840
So we are building a lot of those functions on existing packages of the tidyverse and beyond, such as Broom or in this case, also survival.

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:52.760
The idea is by having this multi-tier approach that you can define a lot of custom features that might be required, such as custom time windows or adding hypothesis tests.

00:34:52.760 --> 00:35:06.560
And so after you have this interim data model, you have the visualization function and then the styling in the end that helps you allow to adhere to those graphical principles that we spoke a bit about before.

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:19.879
And so if you go to the next slide. Mark. Mark, can you go to the next slide or is it stuck just for me?

00:35:19.879 --> 00:35:28.800
All right. Thank you. So this is these were a lot of the design considerations that are definitely not set in stone.

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:32.520
So if people have ideas and thoughts about that, we would love to hear them.

00:35:32.520 --> 00:35:40.479
But Diego will show you now in the next few slides how we implemented the prototype and what those outputs look like for now.

00:35:40.479 --> 00:35:49.000
And with that, I would like I would like to hand over to you, Diego. Thanks, Charlotte.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:36:00.280
Yeah, so so now that Charlotte has introduced the main architecture considerations and the main concepts that we used to design the package.

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:10.520
Let's look at this in the context of a practical application. So let's look at this in the context of a time, your typical time to event analysis workflow.

00:36:10.520 --> 00:36:22.000
And so when we're carrying out these types of analysis analyses, there's a number of steps that will be there virtually every time we carry out these analyses.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:33.879
And all of which require some level of communicating results or communicating interim results and which can be communicated in different ways,

00:36:33.879 --> 00:36:41.120
depending on the audience and depending on the circumstances, as mentioned also by Mark before.

00:36:41.120 --> 00:36:44.560
And so, for example, you might start with something like building your analysis cohort.

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:50.360
So you might want to understand how many patients are kept after applying certain inclusion exclusion criteria.

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:56.600
And you might want to show that by either showing a table or a flow chart.

00:36:56.600 --> 00:37:05.199
Then once you have your analysis cohort, you might want to understand their baseline characteristics of the population that you're analysing.

00:37:05.199 --> 00:37:16.239
And so you might do that using some kind of table one, which is a very popular table that's used in virtually all and virtually every paper out there on these types of studies.

00:37:16.239 --> 00:37:21.479
And then you might be interested in doing some kind of survival analysis.

00:37:21.479 --> 00:37:31.439
And for that, you might plot something like a Kaplan-Meier plot or you might want to show some tables showing the median survival.

00:37:31.439 --> 00:37:43.479
So there are different things that you might want to show as interim results and that all require a certain level of code and programming and effort and time.

00:37:43.479 --> 00:37:49.080
And so we as data scientists spend a lot of time doing redoing these a lot of very often.

00:37:49.080 --> 00:37:54.120
Right. So can we go to the next slide, please?

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:59.600
So now let's look at these one by one. So the first one was building an analysis analysis cohort.

00:37:59.600 --> 00:38:11.639
Right. And so first, the philosophy that we have tried to follow with with this R was that we wanted to, as Charlotte mentioned, not create more work.

00:38:11.639 --> 00:38:26.159
But we also wanted this to implement sort of out of the box best practices and and also reuse the knowledge that we have acquired through our own experience and through interviews that we have carried out.

00:38:26.159 --> 00:38:34.360
And so the way this works, as you can see, you can create a list of filters as well as descriptions.

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:54.159
So that's very so it takes very little code to create your cohort attrition using this R and then really creating a table that shows the attrition just takes basically five lines of code using this function called VR underscore render underscore table.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:39:03.560
And then you can output this nicely formatted table that shows you the relevant information, including the criteria that's being applied.

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:08.840
What's the condition? How many patients are being kept and excluded as well as percentages for these?

00:39:08.840 --> 00:39:17.800
And of course, it comes with nice I mean, it will show nicely formatted titles as well as metadata that might be relevant, such as data sources.

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:27.040
And so you don't have to spend a lot of time thinking of what should I show to what should I show in this plot in order to follow best practices?

00:39:27.040 --> 00:39:41.000
Again, little code, very little code and nicely formatted outputs, best foals, but best practices and reuses knowledge to go to the next slide.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:48.639
So then you might also want to show this in the form of a flowchart, which is a very typical visualization of the attrition diagram.

00:39:48.639 --> 00:39:58.760
And so, again, this takes very little code. You can create a vector of complement descriptions as well as reuse the outputs from the previous chunk of code.

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:10.919
And using this VR underscore attrition function, you can plot this nicely formatted attrition diagram, which shows at each step how many patients have been kept and excluded.

00:40:10.919 --> 00:40:21.080
And this is a very popular, again, figure that shows up in many real world data analysis papers.

00:40:21.080 --> 00:40:31.800
And I should highlight that the that this type of package can help us better comply with reporting guidelines like consort and strobe.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:41.199
Can we go to the next slide, please? So once we have selected our baseline population and our analysis cohort,

00:40:41.199 --> 00:40:46.360
we might want to be interested in showing and understanding the baseline characteristics.

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:51.120
And so this is typically done using the very popular table one.

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:59.840
We looked at a number of implementations of it and we couldn't find one that really satisfied all the requirements that we had.

00:40:59.840 --> 00:41:06.399
So we have created our own. The nice thing about it is that it's very flexible.

00:41:06.399 --> 00:41:19.080
So it comes already with very good inbuilt summary functions that will help you summarize your categorical as well as numerical variables out of the box.

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:27.600
But it also lets you input your own custom built summary functions if they don't satisfy your specific requirement.

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:35.760
It also outputs the tables in different formats, including cable RStudio GT as well as DTHTML tables.

00:41:35.800 --> 00:41:43.239
And importantly, it also lets you download the table one as Excel or CSV,

00:41:43.239 --> 00:41:51.199
which was one of the requests that came the most often when we interviewed our internal scientists.

00:41:51.199 --> 00:42:02.399
And again, it takes very little code. It's about four lines of code and again follows best practices and reuses are the knowledge that we have acquired.

00:42:02.399 --> 00:42:14.199
Can we go to the next slide? So finally, we might be interested or actually next, we should we should we might be interested in none of the same.

00:42:14.199 --> 00:42:19.919
Yeah, we might be interested in doing a survival analysis.

00:42:19.919 --> 00:42:28.800
So this is typically done using a Kaplan-Meier curve together with a risk table.

00:42:28.800 --> 00:42:36.560
And usually there's a number of metadata elements that are important here.

00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:48.760
And so I should highlight that we have based our design of our Kaplan-Meier visualization on the outcome and the findings of a paper by Morris and collaborators

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:56.000
that was conducted among a large number of researchers about what a good Kaplan-Meier plot should look like.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:04.719
And so our Kaplan-Meier plot shows relevant information out of the box, including things like number of patients,

00:43:04.719 --> 00:43:14.280
nicely formatted access labels, including units where needed, as well as a data source from which the plot was made.

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:24.879
It also shows a risk table in a format, including things like numbers, number of patients at risk, number of events and number of censoring events as well,

00:43:24.879 --> 00:43:31.479
grouped by stratum at regular time points. And this format actually follows the recommendations by Morris and collaborators.

00:43:31.479 --> 00:43:39.679
So, again, this is reusing knowledge and best practices can go to the next slide.

00:43:39.679 --> 00:43:45.280
So how do we how do we do this using this R? It's very simple. We have two options.

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:56.360
One is either we plot the Kaplan-Meier curve alone using the first chunk here and then the risk table alone using the second chunk here in the middle.

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:05.360
And both of these show our design philosophy of separating the estimation from the plotting and styling.

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:10.919
But then we also have the option of plotting all of this in one go and one function call.

00:44:10.919 --> 00:44:19.199
And it's the chunk in the bottom here. So this one is just one function call and then gives you that nice plot.

00:44:19.199 --> 00:44:24.760
Again, very little code. It reuses best practices and knowledge.

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:32.560
Can we go to the next slide? So finally, we have also implemented a set of convenient estimation functions,

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:41.120
including median survival times by stratum, as well as multiple methods for testing equality between strata.

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:44.520
And again, you can do this very easily with only a few lines of code.

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:49.520
And it shows you very nicely formatted tables that follow best practices.

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:59.600
Can we go to the next slide? So now going into our packet roadmap,

00:44:59.600 --> 00:45:04.239
I would like to to highlight that this is still a prototype.

00:45:04.239 --> 00:45:14.120
So we are basically reaching now the stage where we are, where we have our prototype that's that's reaching the state where it's ready.

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:23.760
And now we are reaching the stage where we want to launch this initiative out there and find and identify collaborators

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:30.600
to to kickstart the the next step of our projects.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:38.840
Can we go to next slide, please? And so with that, I'd like to announce that we're looking for contributors to join the VisR team.

