00:48:05.959 --> 00:48:13.840
And also there's the Stratos collaboration, which is related to this, which is looking at methodology as a whole for observational data.

00:48:13.840 --> 00:48:21.360
But yes, we would be open to collaborations from any avenues.

00:48:21.360 --> 00:48:30.919
Thank you, Mark. Another question that came in earlier was, when will this package be on CRAN?

00:48:30.919 --> 00:48:36.280
Yeah. Yeah. So as I said, currently it's in prototype stages.

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:44.919
I think we would still have to probably go further into development in order to put it into CRAN.

00:48:44.919 --> 00:48:50.879
But definitely we have it in our radar to do that.

00:48:50.879 --> 00:48:58.000
Thank you. Another question was, what do you mean by join the core team?

00:48:58.040 --> 00:49:03.159
Charlotte. Thank you, Mark.

00:49:03.159 --> 00:49:16.239
Join the core team, I guess, means that at the moment we're this relatively small group of people who had regular meetings around aspects like the package architecture, for example.

00:49:16.239 --> 00:49:23.360
And while you might not want to commit to having those alignment meetings and other aspects,

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:34.360
I guess if you join the core team, this would be part of like driving the general direction of the package, making design choices and things like that.

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:44.120
Whereas if you just picked an issue on GitHub and contributed to it, there would be a little less involvement in the overall direction.

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:50.840
Thank you, Charlotte. So there's two questions which are relatively similar.

00:49:50.840 --> 00:49:55.280
One was, is this focusing on clinical data only?

00:49:55.280 --> 00:50:01.800
And another question, do you have a sub team focused on reporting for real world data?

00:50:01.800 --> 00:50:08.320
So I guess overall, the question is, what's the focus of this effort?

00:50:08.320 --> 00:50:19.479
Mark, do you want to take that one? I would say the general focus at the moment is exploratory analysis of clinical and medical data.

00:50:19.919 --> 00:50:25.800
Probably Diego and Charlotte could back me up here, but they work primarily on real world data.

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:37.479
So it is a mixture of clinical and real world data. Thank you, Mark.

00:50:37.479 --> 00:50:42.800
A quick one was, can you share the link again to those graphical principles?

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:50.159
I will take this one. You can see it on this last slide.

00:50:50.159 --> 00:50:54.679
And here's another one.

00:50:54.679 --> 00:51:06.479
Do you have any recommendations for developing visualisations for different kinds of users, users with different fluency in data, for example?

00:51:06.479 --> 00:51:11.320
Diego, what are your thoughts on this one?

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:21.439
Yeah, I think in general, as Mark mentioned before, it's really about knowing your audience.

00:51:21.439 --> 00:51:27.760
So I really couldn't give you one rule of thumb for everything.

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:33.600
But we definitely, I think just as for how we are handling that with the package,

00:51:33.639 --> 00:51:45.840
that's really part of why we have decided to sort of separate the idea of doing estimates and visualisations and like having multiple ways of presenting a message.

00:51:45.840 --> 00:51:49.760
Because, yeah, as Mark said, really, you should know your audience.

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:57.679
And so that also translates into being able to show things in different or being able to communicate your results in different ways.

00:51:57.679 --> 00:52:04.679
And so that flexibility is something that we want to embed in our project as well.

00:52:04.679 --> 00:52:12.280
Thank you, Diego. I'll move on to a question regarding compatibility.

00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:22.360
Two people have asked about intentions to combine this with LaTeX or somehow create a link to LaTeX.

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:31.080
And on the other hand, whether we are planning to create some templates for reporting with R Markdown.

00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:40.560
So both of the questions maybe can go to Mark.

00:52:40.560 --> 00:52:48.360
Yeah, at the moment, I guess the table one is an example where the engine can change,

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:52.399
but the underlying data or the reporting of the data should not change.

00:52:52.399 --> 00:52:57.479
So I do believe that LaTeX is an option, but hasn't been implemented.

00:52:57.479 --> 00:53:07.040
I possibly need to hand over to Charlotte to confirm, but we would be looking at different engines for reporting.

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:13.600
Yeah, just to add to that, actually, there was and I saw there was another question on the chat about GT summary.

00:53:13.600 --> 00:53:22.199
So the reason why we build our own table rendering was to support different engines, namely Cable, GT and DT.

00:53:22.199 --> 00:53:29.080
And and that is specifically because some of these already come with LaTeX support and that is implemented already,

00:53:29.080 --> 00:53:33.040
at least in the rudimentary form regarding templates.

00:53:33.040 --> 00:53:37.840
I think that's a great idea. We haven't really we haven't really reached that stage yet.

00:53:37.840 --> 00:53:52.439
But we we try to to create the functions at the moment in a flexible way that allows easy integration in different Markdown output formats as well as Shiny.

00:53:52.439 --> 00:53:59.560
Thank you, Mark and Charlotte. Here's the question.

00:53:59.560 --> 00:54:04.879
Is it planned to have only survival analysis or other epidemiological model or analysis?

00:54:04.919 --> 00:54:12.040
I think the answer is clearly, yes, we want to expand to many different types of analysis,

00:54:12.040 --> 00:54:20.199
common ones and gradually, perhaps a little less common ones as well.

00:54:20.199 --> 00:54:29.560
One question I think is important here, just coming in, what level of proficiency are you looking for in contributors?

00:54:29.560 --> 00:54:35.199
Maybe Charlotte, do you want to answer this one? Sure.

00:54:35.199 --> 00:54:39.639
I guess we're we are open for all levels of proficiency.

00:54:39.639 --> 00:54:43.600
So as we said, this this package is at a really early stage.

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:51.840
So we'd love to hear and see people contribute who have who have a lot of experience in developing our packages,

00:54:51.840 --> 00:54:58.280
from which we could probably learn quite a bit, being more in the data science and domain expert side at the moment.

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:08.199
But then also people who come in who would be like target users or who want to write documentation or vignettes are very welcome.

00:55:08.199 --> 00:55:13.439
So all levels of proficiency are welcome to join the team.

00:55:13.439 --> 00:55:17.679
Thank you very much. And maybe a last question, because we only have one minute left.

00:55:17.679 --> 00:55:30.199
Someone has asked about the possibility to incorporate corporate branding, colour schemes and the like on top of the good graphical principles.

00:55:30.199 --> 00:55:36.199
The answer is clearly yes. That's the way the package is designed.

00:55:36.199 --> 00:55:46.919
It is it should be possible to to plug your personal or your company's corporate branding at the very last step on top of the visualisations.

